## .NET Performance Analysis — `MultiLocaleConverters.cs`

**Context:** Hot path — called in tight loops during batch report generation.

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|---|---|
| `.IndexOf(string)` no `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith`/`.EndsWith` no `StringComparison` | **3** |
| `.Contains(string)` no `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| Chained `.Replace()` 3+ | 0 |
| `params` | 0 |
| LINQ `.All`/`.Any` on char | 0 |
| `static readonly Dictionary<` | **3** |
| `static readonly FrozenDictionary<` | 0 |
| Per-call `new List<` | **1** (line 196) |
| Per-call `new Dictionary<` | 0 |
| LINQ chains | 0 |
| `word +=` string concatenation | **17** |
| String interpolation `$"` | 7 |
| Unsealed non-abstract classes | **2** |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| `new Regex(` / `RegexOptions.Compiled` | 0 |

---

### 🟡 Moderate Findings

#### 1. `string +=` concatenation builds O(n) intermediates per call (17 instances)

**Impact:** Each `Convert()` call allocates 5–15 intermediate strings across branches, plus a final `.Trim()` allocation. In tight batch loops this is the dominant allocation source.

**Files:** `MultiLocaleConverters.cs`: L50–L114 (Swedish, ~10 sites), L324–L364 (Hungarian, ~8 sites)

**Fix:** Replace `var word = ""` + `word +=` with `StringBuilder`:

```csharp
// Before (Swedish Convert, same pattern applies to Hungarian)
var word = "";
if (number / 1_000_000_000 > 0)
{
    word += Convert(number / 1_000_000_000) + " miljarder ";
    number %= 1_000_000_000;
}
// ... more word += branches ...
return word.Trim();

// After
var sb = new StringBuilder(64);
if (number / 1_000_000_000 > 0)
{
